---
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="center" style="--scale-from: 3.5;--fragment-duration: 1s">
  <h3
    p-effect="zoom fade"
    style="font-size: 0.6em; opacity: 0.6; margin-block-end: 0.5em;;"
  >
    your MCP server is on the internet now...
  </h3>
  <h2 p-effect="zoom fade" style="font-size: 1.5em;">
    <span class="main-gradient">who's allowed to call it?</span> 🤔
  </h2>
  <p
    p-effect="zoom fade"
    style="font-size: 0.6em; margin-block-start: 1em; opacity: 0.7;"
  >
    The MCP spec answers this with <strong>OAuth 2.1 + PKCE</strong>
  </p>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      stdio is inherently trusted — the host spawns the process itself. But a
      remote HTTP server is exposed to the network, so the MCP spec requires
      OAuth 2.1 with PKCE to authenticate clients properly.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 style="margin-block-end: 0.2rem;" class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
    HTTP -Authentication
  </h2>
  <h3 style="margin-block-start: 0.8rem;">OAuth 2.0 🔐</h3>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h3 class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">
    What is PKCE - Proof Key for Code Exchange?
  </h3>
  <ul>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🧪 Client creates a random <code>code_verifier</code>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      🧬 Sends only a hashed <code>code_challenge</code> during login
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🎫 Sends the original <code>code_verifier</code> when exchanging the code
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      🛡️ Prevents stolen authorization codes from being reused
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      PKCE is an extension to the OAuth Authorization Code flow. The client
      starts by generating a random secret called code_verifier. Instead of
      sending the secret directly, it sends a hashed version called
      code_challenge.
    </p>
    <p>
      Later, when the client exchanges the authorization code for an access
      token, it must send the original code_verifier. The authorization server
      hashes it again and checks that it matches the original challenge.
    </p>
    <p>
      This means that stealing the authorization code is not enough to obtain an
      access token. Without the original verifier, the token exchange fails.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h3 class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">The OAuth flow</h3>
  <ul>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🔍 <span class="main-sub-gradient">1. Discovery</span> — client discovers the
      OAuth metadata
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      👤 <span class="main-sub-gradient">2. Authorization</span> — user logs in and
      grants permission
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🎫 <span class="main-sub-gradient">3. Token exchange</span> — client gets an
      access token
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      ✅ <span class="main-sub-gradient">4. Authenticated requests</span> — token
      sent as <code>Authorization: Bearer</code>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The MCP client kicks off the flow automatically if the server returns 401.
      Discovery tells the client where to redirect the user for login and where
      to exchange the code for a token.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 style="margin-block-end: 1em;">
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">Discovery endpoint</span> 🔍
  </h3>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="/.well-known/oauth-authorization-server">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">
    {
        "issuer": "https://my-mcp-server.com",
        "authorization_endpoint": "https://my-mcp-server.com/oauth/authorize",
        "token_endpoint": "https://my-mcp-server.com/oauth/token",
        "response_types_supported": ["code"],
        "code_challenge_methods_supported": ["S256"]
    }</code>
  </pre>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      This is the metadata document the MCP client fetches first. It tells the
      client where to send the user for login and where to exchange the
      authorization code for a token. S256 is the PKCE method required by the
      spec.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 style="margin-block-end: 0.6em;">
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">Validating the token</span> 🛡️
  </h3>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="server.js">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">//...
    import { betterAuth } from "better-auth";
    import { bearer } from "better-auth/plugins";

    const auth = betterAuth({
    baseURL: process.env.BETTER_AUTH_URL ?? "http://localhost:3000",
    plugins: [bearer()],
    socialProviders: {
        github: {
        clientId: process.env.GITHUB_ID,
        clientSecret: process.env.GITHUB_SECRET,
        },
    },
    });</code>
  </pre>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The bearer() plugin tells better-auth to accept Bearer tokens in the
      Authorization header — exactly what the MCP client sends. No manual token
      verification needed.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide follow-fragments>
  <h3 style="margin-block-end: 1em;">
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all">Protecting the endpoint</span> 🔒
  </h3>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="server.js">
<code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">    const createServer = () => {
    // create server..
    // register tools..
    return server;
    };</code><p-fragment><code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">

    const app = express();
    app.use(express.json());

    app.post("/mcp", async (req, res) => {
    </code><code p-fragment p-effect="highlight" style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">const session = await auth.api.getSession({ headers: req.headers });</code><code style="font-size: 0.6em" is:raw class="language-javascript">

    if (!session?.user) {
        return res.status(401).json({ error: "unauthorized" });
    }

    const transport = new StreamableHTTPServerTransport({ sessionIdGenerator: undefined });
    const server = createServer();
    await server.connect(transport);
    await transport.handleRequest(req, res, req.body);
    });

    app.listen(3000);</code></p-fragment>
  </pre>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Just call getSession() and check if a user is there before handing off to
      the MCP transport. If the session is missing, return 401 — the MCP client
      will kick off the OAuth flow automatically.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<p-slide>
  <h3>
    <span class="cover-internal-sub-section-all"
      >Don't build it from scratch</span
    > 🙏
  </h3>
  <ul>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      📦 <span class="main-sub-gradient">@auth/core</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      ⚡ <span class="main-sub-gradient">better-auth</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      ☁️ <span class="main-sub-gradient">Clerk / Auth0</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      👀 The MCP SDK will soon ship <span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >built-in OAuth helpers</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Implementing OAuth from scratch is error-prone. Use a battle-tested
      library or a hosted provider. The MCP SDK team is also working on built-in
      helpers to make this even simpler in the near future.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
<style lang="scss">
  ul {
    li[p-fragment]:not(:last-of-type) {
      margin-block-end: 0.55em;
    }
  }
</style>
